        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the filing, here are the answers to your specific questions:\n\n**1. Is there any standalone revenue figure or growth metric disclosed for Grok API access revenue specifically?**\n\n**No.** The filing does not provide a standalone revenue figure or growth metric specifically for Grok API access. It is consistently listed as one component of the larger "AI solutions and infrastructure" revenue category, alongside subscriptions and data licensing.\n\n*   **Evidence:** The revenue recognition policy states revenue is generated from "(i) subscription offerings, (ii) data licensing arrangements, and (iii) API access to Grok models." However, the financial performance sections always aggregate these.\n*   **Example:** For FY2025, the increase is attributed to "an increase in X and Grok subscription revenue of $365 million and an increase in revenue from data licensing arrangements of $88 million." API access revenue is not itemized.\n\n**2. Does the filing disclose any ARPU (average revenue per user) metrics for Grok subscribers or X subscribers?**\n\n**No.** The filing does not calculate or disclose ARPU metrics for either Grok or X subscribers.\n\n*   **Evidence:** While the filing provides subscriber counts (e.g., "approximately 6.3 million active paid subscribers" as of March 2026, split between ~4.4 million X subscribers and ~1.9 million Grok subscribers), it does not pair these with standalone revenue figures for each subscriber base that would allow an ARPU calculation.\n*   **Note:** The filing *does* mention a decline in Starlink Subscriber ARPU as part of the Connectivity segment\'s analysis, but no such metric is provided for the AI segment\'s subscription services.\n\n**3. Is there any indication of what portion of the $365 million subscription revenue increase came from Grok vs. X subscriptions in FY2025?**\n\n**No.** The filing does not provide a breakdown of the $365 million subscription revenue increase between Grok and X subscriptions for FY2025. It is consistently reported as a combined "X and Grok subscription revenue" figure.\n\n*   **Evidence:** In the AI segment revenue analysis, the text states: "The increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue is mainly due to an increase in **X and Grok subscription revenue of $365 million**." This combined reporting is repeated in the quarterly analysis for Q1 2026 ("increase in Grok and X subscription revenue of $177 million").\n\n**Summary:** The S-1 excerpts provided are rich in qualitative strategy and aggregated financial figures but lack the granular, standalone disclosures for Grok API revenue, subscriber-level ARPU, or a split of subscription revenue growth between the X and Grok products. This level of detail is typically not required in a prospectus summary or MD&A unless it is material to understanding a distinct business segment, which in this case, the company appears to present as an integrated "AI segment."',
